window.northernIrelandCastles=[{"name":"Dunluce Castle","lat":55.2106,"lng":-6.5794,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"16th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A dramatic ruin perched on basalt cliffs overlooking the Atlantic, Dunluce was the seat of the MacDonnell clan. Part of its kitchen quarters famously fell into the sea during a storm in 1639.","history":"Dunluce Castle is a now-ruined medieval castle in Northern Ireland, the seat of Clan MacQuillan. It is located on the edge of a basalt outcropping in County Antrim, and is accessible via a bridge connecting it to the mainland. The castle is surrounded by extremely steep drops on either side, which may have been an important factor to the early Christians and Vikings who were drawn to this place where an early Irish fort once stood.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/04/Dunluce_Castle_Northern_Ireland_1.jpg/500px-Dunluce_Castle_Northern_Ireland_1.jpg","rating":4.5,"reviewCount":9000,"county":"County Antrim","tags":["dramatic-ruin","photogenic","filming-location"],"access":"paid","_index":334,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/dunluce-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dunluce-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dunluce-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dunluce-castle-5.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dunluce-castle-main-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dunluce-castle-main-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dunluce-castle-main-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dunluce-castle-main-5.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dunluce-castle-keep-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dunluce-castle-keep-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dunluce-castle-keep-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dunluce-castle-keep-5.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dunluce-castle-interior-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dunluce-castle-interior-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dunluce-castle-interior-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dunluce-castle-interior-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Carrickfergus Castle","lat":54.7142,"lng":-5.8067,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"12th century","condition":"intact","description":"One of the best-preserved Norman castles in Ireland, built by John de Courcy around 1177. Guarding Belfast Lough for over 800 years, it saw service through both World Wars.","history":"Carrickfergus Castle is a Norman castle in Northern Ireland, situated in the town of Carrickfergus in County Antrim, on the northern shore of Belfast Lough. Besieged in turn by the Scottish, rebel Irish, English, and French, the castle played an important military role until 1928 and remains one of the best preserved medieval structures in Northern Ireland. It was strategically useful, with 3/4 of the castle perimeter surrounded by water. Today it is maintained by the Department for Communities as a state care historic monument, at grid ref: J4143 8725.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7b/Carrickfergus_Castle%2C_reflections_at_sunset_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1098306.jpg/500px-Carrickfergus_Castle%2C_reflections_at_sunset_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1098306.jpg","rating":4.5,"reviewCount":5600,"county":"County Antrim","tags":["well-preserved","kid-friendly","photogenic"],"access":"paid","_index":335,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/carrickfergus-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/carrickfergus-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/carrickfergus-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/carrickfergus-castle-5.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/carrickfergus-castle-interior-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/carrickfergus-castle-interior-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/carrickfergus-castle-interior-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/carrickfergus-castle-interior-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Enniskillen Castle","lat":54.3436,"lng":-7.64,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"15th century","condition":"intact","description":"A Maguire stronghold on the banks of Lough Erne, featuring the distinctive Watergate with its twin turrets. Now home to the Fermanagh County Museum and the Inniskilling Regimental Museum.","history":"Enniskillen Castle is situated in Enniskillen, County Fermanagh, Northern Ireland. It was originally built in the 16th century and now contains the Fermanagh County Museum and a museum for the 5th Royal Inniskilling Dragoon Guards and Royal Inniskilling Fusiliers.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d3/Enniskillen_Castle_by_Paride.JPG/500px-Enniskillen_Castle_by_Paride.JPG","rating":4.3,"reviewCount":3200,"county":"County Fermanagh","tags":["well-preserved","kid-friendly"],"access":"paid","_index":336,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/enniskillen-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/enniskillen-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/enniskillen-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/enniskillen-castle-5.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/enniskillen-castle-keep-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/enniskillen-castle-keep-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/enniskillen-castle-keep-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/enniskillen-castle-keep-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Dundrum Castle","lat":54.2567,"lng":-5.85,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"12th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A magnificent Norman castle built by John de Courcy on a hilltop overlooking Dundrum Bay and the Mourne Mountains. Its circular keep is one of the finest examples of Anglo-Norman military architecture.","history":"Dundrum Castle, a ruin standing over the town of Dundrum, County Down, Northern Ireland. It was constructed by John de Courcy, sometime near the beginning of the 13th century, following his invasion of Ulster. The castle, built to control access into Lecale from the west and south, stands on the top of a rocky hill commanding fine views south over Dundrum Bay and the Mourne Mountains, the lands west towards Slieve Croob and the plains of Lecale to the east. The Castle is a State Care Historic Monument in the townland of Dundrum, in Newry, Mourne and Down District Council area, at grid ref: J4047 3700.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2d/Dundrum_Castle_from_outside.jpg/500px-Dundrum_Castle_from_outside.jpg","rating":4.4,"reviewCount":2800,"county":"County Down","tags":["dramatic-ruin","photogenic","hidden-gem","free"],"access":"free","_index":337,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/dundrum-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dundrum-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dundrum-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dundrum-castle-5.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dundrum-castle-keep-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dundrum-castle-keep-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dundrum-castle-keep-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dundrum-castle-keep-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Belfast Castle","lat":54.6392,"lng":-5.9431,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"19th century","condition":"intact","description":"A Scottish baronial-style castle on the slopes of Cave Hill overlooking Belfast. Built by the Donegall family in 1870, its cat garden features nine artistic cat representations for good luck.","history":"Belfast Castle is a mansion located in Cave Hill Country Park in Belfast, Northern Ireland, in a prominent position 400 feet (120 m) above sea level. Its location provides unobstructed views over the City of Belfast and Belfast Lough. There have been several structures called \"Belfast Castle\" over the centuries, located on different sites. The current \"castle\" is a Victorian structure that was built between 1867 and 1870 on the slopes of Cave Hill, and it is Grade A listed. The main entrance into the Belfast Castle Demesne is now where Innisfayle Park meets Downview Park West, just off the Antrim Road.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/Belfast_Castle%2C_August_2011.jpg/500px-Belfast_Castle%2C_August_2011.jpg","rating":4.3,"reviewCount":4200,"county":"County Antrim","tags":["well-preserved","free","kid-friendly"],"access":"free","_index":338,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/belfast-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/belfast-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/belfast-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/belfast-castle-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Killyleagh Castle","lat":54.3964,"lng":-5.6531,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"12th century","condition":"intact","description":"Claimed to be the oldest inhabited castle in Ireland, Killyleagh is a fairytale turreted castle overlooking Strangford Lough. It was the childhood home of Hans Sloane, whose collection founded the British Museum.","history":"Killyleagh Castle is a castle in the village of Killyleagh, County Down, Northern Ireland. It is believed to be one of the oldest inhabited castles in the country, with parts dating back to 1180. It follows the architectural style of a Loire Valley château, being redesigned by the architect Sir Charles Lanyon in the mid-19th century. It has been owned by the Hamilton family since the early 17th century.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f9/Tully_Castle%2C_County_Fermanagh_-_geograph.org.uk_-_204216.jpg/500px-Tully_Castle%2C_County_Fermanagh_-_geograph.org.uk_-_204216.jpg","rating":4.2,"reviewCount":1400,"county":"County Down","tags":["well-preserved","photogenic","hidden-gem"],"access":"exterior-only","_index":339,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/killyleagh-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/killyleagh-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/killyleagh-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/killyleagh-castle-5.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/killyleagh-castle-tower-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/killyleagh-castle-tower-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/killyleagh-castle-tower-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/killyleagh-castle-tower-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Narrow Water Castle","lat":54.09,"lng":-6.2558,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"tower house","era":"16th century","condition":"intact","description":"An Elizabethan tower house guarding the narrow stretch of water between Carlingford Lough and the Newry River. Its bawn wall and tower survive complete beside the shore.","history":"Narrow Water Castle is a 16th-century tower house and bawn near Warrenpoint in Northern Ireland. It is beside the A2 road and on the County Down bank of the Clanrye (Newry) River, which enters Carlingford Lough 1-mile (1.6 km) to the south. It is a historic monument in state care in the townland of Narrow Water, in Newry and Mourne District Council district, at grid ref: J1256 1939.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/Monea_Castle1.jpg/500px-Monea_Castle1.jpg","rating":4,"reviewCount":780,"county":"County Down","tags":["well-preserved","hidden-gem"],"access":"exterior-only","_index":340,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/narrow-water-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/narrow-water-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/narrow-water-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/narrow-water-castle-5.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/narrow-water-castle-keep-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/narrow-water-castle-keep-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/narrow-water-castle-keep-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/narrow-water-castle-keep-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Greencastle Royal Castle","lat":54.0744,"lng":-6.1289,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"13th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A royal castle built by Hugh de Lacy in the 1230s to guard the entrance to Carlingford Lough. Its massive keep and rock-cut ditch reflect its strategic importance.","history":"Greencastle is a castle in County Down, Northern Ireland. While it dates mainly from the 13th century, it had substantial 15th- and 16th-century alterations. It was originally surrounded by outer rectangular walls with four corner towers. It is likely to have been built by Hugh de Lacy, along with Carlingford Castle on the opposite side of Carlingford Lough, to guard the narrow entry channel to the Lough, and the ferry crossing between the two.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f0/Maghera_Church_-_geograph.org.uk_-_222328.jpg/500px-Maghera_Church_-_geograph.org.uk_-_222328.jpg","rating":4,"reviewCount":680,"county":"County Down","tags":["dramatic-ruin","hidden-gem","free"],"access":"free","_index":341,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/greencastle-royal-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/greencastle-royal-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/greencastle-royal-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/greencastle-royal-castle-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Audley's Castle","lat":54.3803,"lng":-5.5553,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"tower house","era":"15th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A 15th-century tower house overlooking Strangford Lough, used as a filming location for Game of Thrones. The Audley family built it to command views of the lough's narrows.","history":"Audley's Castle is a 15th-century castle located 1 mile (1.6 km) north-east of Strangford, County Down, Northern Ireland, on a rocky height overlooking Strangford Lough. It is a three-storey Tower house named after its 16th century owner, John Audley. Audley's Castle tower house and bawn is a State Care Historic Monument in the townland of Castleward, in Down District Council area, at grid ref: J5781 5058.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3f/Ballygally_Castle.jpg/500px-Ballygally_Castle.jpg","rating":4.1,"reviewCount":1200,"county":"County Down","tags":["dramatic-ruin","filming-location","hidden-gem","free"],"access":"free","_index":342,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/audley-s-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/audley-s-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/audley-s-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/audley-s-castle-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Inch Abbey","lat":54.3333,"lng":-5.7333,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"abbey","era":"12th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A Cistercian abbey founded by John de Courcy around 1180 in a beautiful riverside setting near Downpatrick. Its Gothic arches and nave ruins were featured in Game of Thrones.","history":"Inch Abbey is a ruined Cistercian monastery on the outskirts of Downpatrick, County Down, Northern Ireland. It was founded by John de Courcy in the 12th-century. It was dissolved in 1541.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/View_of_Antrim_Castle_from_the_river_%2813733537463%29.jpg/500px-View_of_Antrim_Castle_from_the_river_%2813733537463%29.jpg","rating":4.2,"reviewCount":1600,"county":"County Down","tags":["romantic-ruin","filming-location","hidden-gem","free"],"access":"free","_index":343,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/inch-abbey-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/inch-abbey-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/inch-abbey-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/inch-abbey-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Jordan's Castle","lat":54.1833,"lng":-5.85,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"tower house","era":"15th century","condition":"partial ruin","description":"One of several tower houses in the medieval town of Ardglass, Jordan's Castle is the best preserved. It served as a fortified warehouse for the town's once-thriving fishing trade.","history":"Jordan's Castle is a castle situated in Ardglass, County Down, Northern Ireland. The tower house known as Jordan's Castle is a State Care Historic Monument sited in the townland of Ardglass, in the Newry, Mourne and Down District Council area, at grid ref: J5601 3713. It stands close to the junction of Kildare and Quay Streets in Ardglass and commands the harbour.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/91/Moyry_Castle_1.jpg/500px-Moyry_Castle_1.jpg","rating":3.7,"reviewCount":420,"county":"County Down","tags":["dramatic-ruin","hidden-gem"],"access":"exterior-only","_index":345,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/jordan-s-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/jordan-s-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/jordan-s-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/jordan-s-castle-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Hillsborough Fort","lat":54.4608,"lng":-6.0839,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"17th century","condition":"intact","description":"A star-shaped artillery fort set in lush parkland, built to command the old road from Dublin to Carrickfergus. Its elegant Georgian gazebo crowns earthworks that once bristled with cannon.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/hillsborough-fort.jpg","rating":4,"reviewCount":980,"county":"County Down","tags":["well-preserved","free-entry","woodland","gardens"],"access":"free","_index":346,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/hillsborough-fort-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/hillsborough-fort-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/hillsborough-fort-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/hillsborough-fort-5.jpg"],"history":"Founded in 1630 by Peter Hill and completed c.1650 by Colonel Arthur Hill to control the strategic Dublin–Carrickfergus road. The Hill family shaped the village of Hillsborough around it. Remodelled in the 18th century with a Gothic-style gazebo, it saw action during the 1641 rebellion. Now set within Hillsborough Forest Park beside the royal residence of Hillsborough Castle.","sources":[{"name":"Discover Northern Ireland","url":"https://discovernorthernireland.com/things-to-do/hillsborough-fort-p686641"},{"name":"Virtual Visit Tours","url":"https://www.virtualvisittours.com/hillsborough-fort/"},{"name":"Wikipedia – Royal Hillsborough","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Royal_Hillsborough"}]},{"name":"Clough Castle","lat":54.2833,"lng":-5.8833,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"12th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A Norman motte and stone castle overlooking the junction of two major roads near Dundrum. Its small stone keep sits atop a prominent mound, a textbook example of early Norman fortification.","history":"Clough Castle is a 12th century Anglo-Norman motte-and-bailey castle located in Clough, County Down, Northern Ireland. It consists of a ruined tower house situated on a 7.6 metres (25 ft) high motte. A small crescent-shaped bailey lies next to the south-east of the motte, separated by a 2.1 metres deep ditch.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c0/Clough_%2811%29%2C_October_2009.JPG/500px-Clough_%2811%29%2C_October_2009.JPG","rating":3.6,"reviewCount":320,"county":"County Down","tags":["romantic-ruin","hidden-gem","free"],"access":"free","_index":347,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/clough-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/clough-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/clough-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/clough-castle-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Sketrick Castle","lat":54.4667,"lng":-5.6333,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"tower house","era":"15th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A tower house ruin on a tidal island in Strangford Lough, accessible at low tide. The castle was built to control maritime trade and fishing rights in the lough.","history":"Sketrick Castle is a castle situated on Sketrick Island near Whiterock, County Down, Northern Ireland. The castle is estimated to date back to the 12th century. Sketrick Castle tower-house and the passage to spring are State Care Historic Monuments in the townland of Sketrick Island, in the Ards and North Down Borough, located at grid reference: J5245 6252.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a5/Sketrick_Castle.jpg","rating":3.5,"reviewCount":240,"county":"County Down","tags":["romantic-ruin","hidden-gem","free"],"access":"free","_index":348,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/sketrick-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/sketrick-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/sketrick-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/sketrick-castle-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Olderfleet Castle","lat":54.8531,"lng":-5.7989,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"tower house","era":"16th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A small but striking tower house ruin on the waterfront at Larne, marking the site of an ancient harbour. Edward Bruce landed here in 1315 during the Scottish invasion of Ireland.","history":"Olderfleet Castle is a four-storey towerhouse, the remains of which stand on Curran Point to the south of Larne Harbour in Larne, County Antrim, Northern Ireland. The place name of Olderfleet may be a corruption of Ulfrecksfiord, the Viking name for Larne Lough.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6f/Ruins_of_Olderfleet_Castle%2C_Larne.jpg/500px-Ruins_of_Olderfleet_Castle%2C_Larne.jpg","rating":3.4,"reviewCount":280,"county":"County Antrim","tags":["romantic-ruin","hidden-gem","free"],"access":"free","_index":350,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/olderfleet-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/olderfleet-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/olderfleet-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/olderfleet-castle-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Shane's Castle","lat":54.7167,"lng":-6.3167,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"17th century","condition":"ruin","description":"The O'Neill family seat on the shores of Lough Neagh, destroyed by fire in 1816. Its extensive demesne and Gothic tower ruins sit in parkland now famous for its nature reserve.","history":"Shane's Castle is a ruined castle near Antrim in County Antrim, Northern Ireland, which was mostly destroyed in 1816 by fire. The castle is situated on the north-east shores of Lough Neagh, 2.7 miles from Randalstown. Built in 1345 by a member of the Clandeboy O'Neill dynasty, it was originally known as Edenduffcarrick, meaning \"brow of black rock\". It owes its present name to Shane McBrian McPhelim O'Neill, who ruled Lower Clandeboy between 1595 and 1617.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8d/Shane%27s_Castle%2C_County_Antrim_-_geograph.org.uk_-_155426.jpg/500px-Shane%27s_Castle%2C_County_Antrim_-_geograph.org.uk_-_155426.jpg","rating":3.8,"reviewCount":560,"county":"County Antrim","tags":["romantic-ruin","hidden-gem"],"access":"exterior-only","_index":351,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/shane-s-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/shane-s-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/shane-s-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/shane-s-castle-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Glenarm Castle","lat":54.9667,"lng":-5.95,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"17th century","condition":"intact","description":"Seat of the Earls of Antrim, Glenarm Castle sits in the oldest of the nine Glens of Antrim. Its walled garden has been restored and opens to the public each summer.","history":"Glenarm Castle, Glenarm, County Antrim, Northern Ireland, is the ancestral home of the Earl of Antrim.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/76/Glenarm_Castle.jpg/500px-Glenarm_Castle.jpg","rating":4.1,"reviewCount":1200,"county":"County Antrim","tags":["well-preserved","hidden-gem"],"access":"paid","_index":352,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/glenarm-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/glenarm-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/glenarm-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/glenarm-castle-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Kinbane Castle","lat":55.225,"lng":-6.2306,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"16th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A MacDonnell castle ruin on a dramatic chalk headland jutting into the sea near Ballycastle. Built in 1547 by Colla MacDonnell, it was twice besieged and captured by the English.","history":"Kinbane Castle is located in County Antrim, Northern Ireland, on a headland between Ballycastle and Ballintoy. The name comes from the Irish for \"white head\", referring to the limestone of the promontory. Nowadays, the castle is largely destroyed. Kinbane Castle is a State Care Historic Monument sited in the townland of Cregganboy, in Moyle District Council area, at grid ref: D0876 4383. The area surrounding Kinbane Castle is a Scheduled Historic Monument, grid ref: D0879 4381. The site also has views of Rathlin Island and Dunagregor Iron Age fort.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/04/Kinbane_Castle%2C_daylight.jpg/500px-Kinbane_Castle%2C_daylight.jpg","rating":4.3,"reviewCount":1600,"county":"County Antrim","tags":["dramatic-ruin","photogenic","hidden-gem","free"],"access":"free","_index":353,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/kinbane-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/kinbane-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/kinbane-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/kinbane-castle-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Dunineny Castle","lat":55.2,"lng":-6.25,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"tower house","era":"15th-16th century","condition":"ruin","description":"Crumbling sea-battered ruins on the Antrim coast, once the stronghold of the MacDonnell chiefs who commanded galleys from Scotland across the narrow strait to Ireland.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/dunineny-castle.jpg","rating":3.2,"reviewCount":120,"county":"County Antrim","tags":["ruins-romantic","coastal","remote","free-entry"],"access":"free","_index":354,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/dunineny-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dunineny-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dunineny-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dunineny-castle-5.jpg"],"history":"Also known as Dunaneeny Castle (Dún an Aonaigh), it was established by Alexander MacDonnell as the seat of Clan MacDonald of Dunnyveg overlooking Port Brittas (Ballycastle Bay). Scottish galleys from Kintyre sheltered in the bay below. Local tradition suggests an earlier O'Carroll fortress on the site. The castle declined after the MacDonnells built a new castle at Ballycastle in the early 1600s.","sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia – Dunaneeny Castle","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dunaneeny_Castle"},{"name":"Art Ward Photography","url":"https://www.artwardphotography.com/dunaneeny-castle"}]},{"name":"Red Bay Castle","lat":55.0667,"lng":-6.05,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"13th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A Norman castle ruin overlooking the picturesque Red Bay in the Glens of Antrim. Built by the Bissets, only fragments of the tower survive on a rocky promontory.","history":"Red Bay Castle is situated in County Antrim, Northern Ireland, on a headland projecting into the sea north of Glenariff situated on the road to Cushendall.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/af/The_ruins_of_Red_Bay_Castle_-_geograph.org.uk_-_3727864.jpg/500px-The_ruins_of_Red_Bay_Castle_-_geograph.org.uk_-_3727864.jpg","rating":3.5,"reviewCount":340,"county":"County Antrim","tags":["romantic-ruin","hidden-gem","free"],"access":"free","_index":355,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/red-bay-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/red-bay-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/red-bay-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/red-bay-castle-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Bonamargy Friary","lat":55.2,"lng":-6.2417,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"abbey","era":"15th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A Franciscan friary near Ballycastle founded around 1485 by Rory MacQuillan. Several MacDonnell chieftains are buried here, including the legendary warrior Sorley Boy MacDonnell.","history":"Bonamargy Friary is situated in County Antrim, Northern Ireland, off the Cushendall Road on the approach to Ballycastle. The name Bonamargy means ‘foot of the Margy River’, the river formed by the joining of the Cary River and Shesk Rivers.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8b/BonamargyFriary.JPG/500px-BonamargyFriary.JPG","rating":4,"reviewCount":680,"county":"County Antrim","tags":["romantic-ruin","hidden-gem","free"],"access":"free","_index":356,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/bonamargy-friary-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/bonamargy-friary-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/bonamargy-friary-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/bonamargy-friary-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Dungannon Castle","lat":54.5083,"lng":-6.7667,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"12th-17th century","condition":"ruin","description":"The ancient hilltop seat of the O'Neill dynasty, chief lords of Ulster. Though the medieval castle is gone, the wooded mound still radiates centuries of Gaelic power and defiance.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/dungannon-castle.jpg","rating":3.4,"reviewCount":280,"county":"County Tyrone","tags":["hilltop","free-entry","atmospheric"],"access":"free","_index":357,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/dungannon-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dungannon-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dungannon-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dungannon-castle-5.jpg"],"history":"Dungannon was the principal stronghold of the O'Neill chieftains for over 400 years. Hugh O'Neill, Earl of Tyrone, made it his base during the Nine Years' War (1594–1603) against Elizabeth I. After the Flight of the Earls in 1607, the castle was seized and rebuilt by English planters but later destroyed. The current hilltop park preserves the castle mound with views over County Tyrone.","sources":[{"name":"Discover Northern Ireland","url":"https://discovernorthernireland.com/things-to-do/dungannon-castle"},{"name":"Wikipedia – Dungannon","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dungannon"}]},{"name":"Castlederg Castle","lat":54.7167,"lng":-7.5833,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"17th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A Plantation-era castle built by Sir John Davies near the confluence of the Derg and Strule rivers. The bawn wall and corner tower survive from the original fortified settlement.","history":"Derg Castle, also called Castlederg Castle, is a post-medieval ruined fortification, situated on the north bank of the River Derg, within the town of Castlederg, in County Tyrone, Northern Ireland. It has given the town its name: 'Castlederg' derives from the Irish Caisleán na Deirge, meaning 'Castle on the Derg'.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/castlederg-castle.jpg","rating":3.3,"reviewCount":180,"county":"County Tyrone","tags":["romantic-ruin","hidden-gem","free"],"access":"free","_index":359,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/castlederg-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/castlederg-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/castlederg-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/castlederg-castle-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Benburb Castle","lat":54.4,"lng":-6.8833,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"17th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A Plantation castle overlooking a dramatic cliff above the River Blackwater, site of Owen Roe O'Neill's famous victory over the Scots in 1646. The castle ruins and servery priory grounds offer spectacular views.","history":"Benburb Castle is a castle situated in Benburb, County Tyrone, Northern Ireland. It is built on a limestone cliff overlooking the River Blackwater, the border between County Tyrone and County Armagh. A 19th-century tower house occupies the south west area of the bawn. The castle has been restored and stands in the grounds of the imposing Servite Priory, the local base of that religious order.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/59/Benburb-Castle-1.jpg/500px-Benburb-Castle-1.jpg","rating":4,"reviewCount":680,"county":"County Tyrone","tags":["dramatic-ruin","hidden-gem","free"],"access":"free","_index":360,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/benburb-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/benburb-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/benburb-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/benburb-castle-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Tully Castle","lat":54.4333,"lng":-7.7333,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"fortified house","era":"17th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A Scottish Planter fortified house on the shores of Lower Lough Erne, burnt during the 1641 Rising. Its restored formal garden recreates a 17th-century planting scheme.","history":"Tully Castle is a castle situated in County Fermanagh, Northern Ireland, near the village of Blaney, on Blaney Bay on the southern shore of Lower Lough Erne. The Blaney area takes its name from Sir Edward Blaney, who was among the English advance party sent to Fermanagh to organise the Plantation.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f9/Tully_Castle%2C_County_Fermanagh_-_geograph.org.uk_-_204216.jpg/500px-Tully_Castle%2C_County_Fermanagh_-_geograph.org.uk_-_204216.jpg","rating":4.1,"reviewCount":780,"county":"County Fermanagh","tags":["romantic-ruin","hidden-gem","free"],"access":"free","_index":361,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/tully-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/tully-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/tully-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/tully-castle-5.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/tully-castle-keep-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/tully-castle-keep-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/tully-castle-keep-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/tully-castle-keep-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Crom Castle","lat":54.1667,"lng":-7.45,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"19th century","condition":"intact","description":"A Victorian castle in a stunning 2,000-acre estate on the shores of Upper Lough Erne. The old castle ruins and ancient yew trees date back centuries earlier than the present house.","history":"  Crom Castle is a country house on the shores of Upper Lough Erne in County Fermanagh, Northern Ireland. It is the seat of the Earls Erne.  Standing within the 1,900-acre (7.7 km2) Crom Estate and a formal garden, the castle is built of stone. A central battlemented tower includes the main entrance, and there are also smaller towers to one side. It stands apart from the ruins of Old Crom Castle, of which two towers, some walls, and a ha-ha survive, and near two ancient yew trees believed to be at least 800 years old.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/crom-castle.jpg","rating":4.3,"reviewCount":1400,"county":"County Fermanagh","tags":["well-preserved","photogenic","hidden-gem"],"access":"paid","_index":362,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/crom-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/crom-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/crom-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/crom-castle-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Monea Castle","lat":54.3667,"lng":-7.6833,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"17th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A striking Plantation castle with Scottish-style cylindrical corner towers, built by Malcolm Hamilton around 1618. Its distinctive silhouette is one of Fermanagh's most photographed landmarks.","history":"   Monea Castle is a castle located in Monea, County Fermanagh, Northern Ireland. It is a State Care Historic Monument situated in the townland of Castletown Monea, in Fermanagh District Council area, at grid ref: H1647 4937.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/monea-castle.jpg","rating":4.2,"reviewCount":980,"county":"County Fermanagh","tags":["dramatic-ruin","photogenic","hidden-gem","free"],"access":"free","_index":363,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/monea-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/monea-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/monea-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/monea-castle-5.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/monea-castle-keep-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/monea-castle-keep-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/monea-castle-keep-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/monea-castle-keep-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Devenish Monastic Site","lat":54.35,"lng":-7.6,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"abbey","era":"6th century","condition":"ruin","description":"An island monastery on Lower Lough Erne founded by St Molaise in the 6th century. Its round tower, Augustinian priory, and high cross make it one of Ulster's most important monastic sites.","history":"Devenish or Devinish is a lake island in Lower Lough Erne, County Fermanagh, Northern Ireland. Aligned roughly north–south, it is about one and a quarter miles (2.0 km) long and two-thirds of a mile (1.1 km) wide.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/devenish-monastic-site.jpg","rating":4.4,"reviewCount":1600,"county":"County Fermanagh","tags":["dramatic-ruin","photogenic","hidden-gem"],"access":"paid","_index":364,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/devenish-monastic-site-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/devenish-monastic-site-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/devenish-monastic-site-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/devenish-monastic-site-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Dungiven Priory","lat":54.9333,"lng":-6.9167,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"abbey","era":"12th-15th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A hauntingly beautiful Augustinian priory ruin sheltering one of Northern Ireland's finest medieval tombs—the ornate canopied effigy of an O'Cahan warrior chief.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/dungiven-priory.jpg","rating":4.1,"reviewCount":680,"county":"County Londonderry","tags":["ruins-romantic","atmospheric","medieval","free-entry"],"access":"free","_index":366,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/dungiven-priory-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dungiven-priory-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dungiven-priory-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dungiven-priory-5.jpg"],"history":"Founded c.1150 by the O'Cahan (Ó Catháin) chiefs, lords of the region until the 17th century. The church contains the magnificent tomb of Cooey-na-Gall O'Cahan, who died in 1385, featuring a carved effigy beneath an elaborate canopy decorated with gallowglass warriors. The priory was suppressed at the Dissolution and later incorporated into a mansion by the Skinners' Company during the Plantation.","sources":[{"name":"Visit Causeway Coast & Glens","url":"https://www.visitcausewaycoastandglens.com/things-to-do/dungiven-priory-and-ocahans-tomb-p675671"},{"name":"RatedTrips","url":"https://www.ratedtrips.com/things-to-do/northern-ireland/county-londonderry-derry/dungiven/dungiven-priory"}]},{"name":"Limavady Roe Valley Castle","lat":55.05,"lng":-6.95,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"17th century","condition":"ruin","description":"The remains of an O'Cahan stronghold and later Plantation castle in the Roe Valley. The site overlooks the river where legend says the famous Londonderry Air was first heard.","history":"Limavady is a market town in County Londonderry, Northern Ireland, with Binevenagh as a backdrop. Lying 17 miles (27 km) east of Derry and 14 miles (23 km) southwest of Coleraine, Limavady had a population of 11,279 people at the 2021 Census. In the 40 years between 1971 and 2011, Limavady's population nearly doubled. Limavady is within Causeway Coast and Glens Borough.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/limavady-roe-valley-castle.jpg","rating":3.4,"reviewCount":220,"county":"County Londonderry","tags":["romantic-ruin","hidden-gem","free"],"access":"free","_index":367,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/limavady-roe-valley-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/limavady-roe-valley-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/limavady-roe-valley-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/limavady-roe-valley-castle-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Maghera Old Church","lat":54.85,"lng":-6.6667,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"abbey","era":"6th century","condition":"ruin","description":"An early monastic site with a remarkable carved Romanesque doorway featuring a Crucifixion scene. Founded by St Lurach, the carved lintel is one of the finest examples of Irish Romanesque art.","history":"Maghera Old Church is the ruins of a church in Maghera, County Londonderry, Northern Ireland. It is a scheduled monument and a Monument in State Care. It was originally founded by St Lurach at some point during the 6th century, likely as a monastery. It is mentioned in the Annals of Ulster when it was plundered by Vikings in 832 and many of its abbots killed. The church later suffered significant damaged when it was burned in 1135.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f0/Maghera_Church_-_geograph.org.uk_-_222328.jpg/500px-Maghera_Church_-_geograph.org.uk_-_222328.jpg","rating":3.9,"reviewCount":340,"county":"County Londonderry","tags":["romantic-ruin","hidden-gem","free"],"access":"free","_index":368,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/maghera-old-church-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/maghera-old-church-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/maghera-old-church-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/maghera-old-church-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Antrim Castle Gardens","lat":54.7167,"lng":-6.2167,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"17th century","condition":"partial ruin","description":"Though the castle itself was destroyed by fire in 1922, the magnificent Anglo-Dutch water gardens survive. The restored parterre, canals, and wilderness garden are among the finest of their kind in the British Isles.","history":"Antrim Castle or Massereene Castle was a fortified mansion in Antrim, County Antrim, Northern Ireland, on the banks of the Sixmilewater River. It was built in stages between 1613 and 1662. It was destroyed by fire in 1922 and finally demolished in the 1970s. All that remains are a slightly raised grassed platform as well as a freestanding Italian stair tower built in 1887, and a gatehouse built around 1818 with twin neo-Tudor towers, with older connecting walls. The gardens are a popular tourist attraction on the Randalstown Road in Antrim.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/View_of_Antrim_Castle_from_the_river_%2813733537463%29.jpg/500px-View_of_Antrim_Castle_from_the_river_%2813733537463%29.jpg","rating":4.3,"reviewCount":2200,"county":"County Antrim","tags":["photogenic","kid-friendly","free","hidden-gem"],"access":"free","_index":370,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/antrim-castle-gardens-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/antrim-castle-gardens-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/antrim-castle-gardens-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/antrim-castle-gardens-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Carrick Castle","lat":54.45,"lng":-6.7833,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"13th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A small but atmospheric Norman castle ruin near the shores of Lough Neagh. Its tower fragments overlook the surrounding drumlins of mid-Armagh.","history":"Carrick Castle is a 14th-century tower house on the west shore of Loch Goil on the Cowal Peninsula, in Argyll and Bute, west of Scotland. It is located between Cuilmuich and Carrick, 4 miles (6.4 km) south of Lochgoilhead.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/Carrick_Castle_tower_from_west.jpg/500px-Carrick_Castle_tower_from_west.jpg","rating":3.3,"reviewCount":160,"county":"County Armagh","tags":["romantic-ruin","hidden-gem","free"],"access":"free","_index":371,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/carrick-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/carrick-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/carrick-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/carrick-castle-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Moyry Castle","lat":54.0667,"lng":-6.35,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"17th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A small English garrison tower built in 1601 to guard the Gap of the North during the Nine Years' War. Lord Mountjoy erected it to control the vital pass between Ulster and the Pale.","history":"Moyry Castle is a small 17th century castle in County Armagh, Northern Ireland. It was built during the latter stages of the Nine Years' War in June 1601 by Lord Mountjoy to help secure Moyry Pass and the Gap of the North. It is set in the corner of a small bawn and is a rectangular tower three storeys high.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/91/Moyry_Castle_1.jpg/500px-Moyry_Castle_1.jpg","rating":3.7,"reviewCount":380,"county":"County Armagh","tags":["dramatic-ruin","hidden-gem","free"],"access":"free","_index":372,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/moyry-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/moyry-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/moyry-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/moyry-castle-5.jpg"]},{"name":"Grey Abbey","lat":54.4917,"lng":-5.5417,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"abbey","era":"12th-16th century","condition":"ruin","description":"Graceful Gothic ruins in a peaceful garden setting on the Ards Peninsula—one of the finest and most complete Cistercian monasteries in Ulster.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/grey-abbey.jpg","rating":4.1,"reviewCount":680,"county":"County Down","tags":["ruins-romantic","gothic","gardens","atmospheric","free-entry"],"access":"free","_index":577,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/grey-abbey-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/grey-abbey-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/grey-abbey-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/grey-abbey-5.jpg"],"history":"Founded in 1193 by Affreca, wife of the Anglo-Norman knight John de Courcy, after she survived a stormy sea crossing. The abbey is one of the first fully Gothic buildings in Ireland, featuring elegant lancet windows and a carved west doorway. It was dissolved in 1541 and later used as a parish church. The surrounding 18th-century physic garden has been restored with period medicinal herbs.","sources":[{"name":"Discover Northern Ireland","url":"https://discovernorthernireland.com/things-to-do/grey-abbey-p675231"},{"name":"Wikipedia – Grey Abbey","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grey_Abbey"}]},{"name":"Mahee Castle","lat":54.472,"lng":-5.664,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"16th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A compact tower house ruin on an island in Strangford Lough, neighbour to the ancient monastery of Nendrum—a place where early Christian and Elizabethan histories quietly overlap.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b0/Mahee_Castle%2C_January_2011_%2801%29.JPG/500px-Mahee_Castle%2C_January_2011_%2801%29.JPG","rating":3.5,"reviewCount":85,"county":"County Down","tags":["ruins-romantic","island","atmospheric","free-entry"],"access":"free","_index":782,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/mahee-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/mahee-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/mahee-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/mahee-castle-5.jpg"],"history":"Built in 1570 by Captain Thomas Browne on Mahee Island in Strangford Lough, County Down. The tower house stands near the far older Nendrum Monastery, a 5th-century monastic site. Abandoned by the early 17th century, the castle fell into ruin. The island is connected to the mainland by causeways and offers peaceful views across the lough.","sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia – Mahee Castle","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mahee_Castle"},{"name":"Belfast Entries","url":"https://www.belfastentries.com/places/historical-places/mahee-castle/"}]},{"name":"Quoile Castle","lat":54.358,"lng":-5.73,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"16th-17th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A sturdy riverside tower house near Downpatrick, its collapsed corner revealing a cross-section of 16th-century construction like a geological slice through time.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/Quoile_Castle%2C_geograph.jpg/500px-Quoile_Castle%2C_geograph.jpg","rating":3.5,"reviewCount":95,"county":"County Down","tags":["ruins-romantic","riverside","free-entry"],"access":"free","_index":783,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/quoile-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/quoile-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/quoile-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/quoile-castle-5.jpg"],"history":"A late 16th / early 17th-century tower house on the east bank of the River Quoile, near Downpatrick, County Down. Possibly built by Captain Richard West, it was inhabited into the 18th century. The south corner has dramatically fallen away, exposing the interior structure. Now part of the Quoile Pondage Nature Reserve, it stands amid wetlands rich in birdlife.","sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia – Quoile Castle","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quoile_Castle"},{"name":"Spotting History","url":"https://www.spottinghistory.com/view/8796/quoile-castle/"}]},{"name":"Cranfield Church","lat":54.668,"lng":-6.515,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"church","era":"13th-14th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A lonesome medieval church ruin on the windswept southern shore of Lough Neagh, where pilgrims once came to collect holy clay believed to cure ailments.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/cranfield-church.jpg","rating":3.3,"reviewCount":18,"county":"County Antrim","tags":["ruins-romantic","atmospheric","free-entry","remote"],"access":"free","_index":1218,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/cranfield-church-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/cranfield-church-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/cranfield-church-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/cranfield-church-5.jpg"],"history":"The ruins of a medieval church dedicated to St Olcan on the southern shore of Lough Neagh, County Antrim. Pilgrims visited for centuries to collect clay from beneath the church floor, believed to have healing properties and to ward off evil. The tradition of taking Cranfield clay continued into modern times. The atmospheric ruin stands in an ancient graveyard with views across Ireland's largest lake.","sources":[{"name":"Discover Northern Ireland","url":"https://discovernorthernireland.com/things-to-do/cranfield-church"},{"name":"Wikipedia – Cranfield Church","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cranfield_Church"}]},{"name":"Donegore Motte","lat":54.692,"lng":-6.148,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"motte","era":"Neolithic / 12th century","condition":"intact","description":"One of Ireland's finest Anglo-Norman mottes rising from the Antrim countryside, offering far-reaching views and hiding layers of history from Neolithic to medieval.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/donegore-motte.jpg","rating":3.2,"reviewCount":14,"county":"County Antrim","tags":["hilltop","free-entry","prehistoric","norman"],"access":"free","_index":1219,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/donegore-motte-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/donegore-motte-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/donegore-motte-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/donegore-motte-5.jpg"],"history":"A large Anglo-Norman motte near Donegore, County Antrim, likely raised in the late 12th century by John de Courcy or his followers during the Norman invasion of Ulster. Archaeological investigations revealed a much older history—Neolithic occupation dating to c.4000 BC makes this one of Ireland's earliest known settlement sites. The motte offers panoramic views over the Six Mile Water valley.","sources":[{"name":"Discover Northern Ireland","url":"https://discovernorthernireland.com/things-to-do/donegore-motte"},{"name":"Wikipedia – Donegore","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donegore"}]},{"name":"Dunadry Castle","lat":54.688,"lng":-6.178,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"tower house","era":"Early medieval","condition":"ruin","description":"Little remains of this early fort near the Six Mile Water in County Antrim, but its name—Dún Eadradh, 'middle fort'—hints at a lost network of strongholds guarding the approaches to Lough Neagh.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/dunadry-castle.jpg","rating":3,"reviewCount":8,"county":"County Antrim","tags":["free-entry","riverside"],"access":"free","_index":1220,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/dunadry-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dunadry-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dunadry-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dunadry-castle-5.jpg"],"history":"Dunadry (from Irish Dún Eadradh, 'middle fort') is a hamlet 3 miles from Antrim town. The name suggests an early Irish ringfort or fortification, part of a chain defending the Six Mile Water valley. Little structural evidence of the original fort survives. The area later became associated with linen milling and the Dunadry Inn, built on the site of an old mill.","sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia – Dunadry","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dunadry"}]},{"name":"Crumlin Castle","lat":54.632,"lng":-6.218,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"motte","era":"12th-13th century","condition":"intact","description":"A vanished Anglo-Norman stronghold in the Crumlin valley of County Antrim—now just a place name echoing the old frontier between Gaelic Ulster and the English Pale.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/crumlin-castle.jpg","rating":3,"reviewCount":7,"county":"County Antrim","tags":["free-entry","norman"],"access":"free","_index":1221,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/crumlin-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/crumlin-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/crumlin-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/crumlin-castle-5.jpg"],"history":"Crumlin (from Irish Cromghlinn, 'crooked glen') in County Antrim was an Anglo-Norman settlement with a castle likely dating to the late 12th or 13th century, part of the network established during the conquest of Ulster. Little survives above ground. The village sits on the River Crumlin near Lough Neagh and retains its medieval street pattern.","sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia – Crumlin, County Antrim","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crumlin,_County_Antrim"}]},{"name":"Drumena Cashel","lat":54.285,"lng":-5.968,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"cashel","era":"6th-12th century","condition":"intact","description":"A beautifully restored early Christian stone fort near Castlewellan, its thick oval walls and souterrain passage offering a tangible connection to daily life in Ireland over a thousand years ago.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/drumena-cashel.jpg","rating":3.5,"reviewCount":30,"county":"County Down","tags":["well-preserved","celtic","free-entry","prehistoric"],"access":"free","_index":1222,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/drumena-cashel-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/drumena-cashel-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/drumena-cashel-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/drumena-cashel-5.jpg"],"history":"An oval stone cashel (fort) measuring 40 x 32 metres, located southwest of Castlewellan overlooking Lough Reavy, County Down. Dating to the early Christian period (c. 500-1200 AD), it was excavated and partially reconstructed in the 1920s. The walls are about 3 metres thick and 2.75 metres high. Inside are foundations of a house and a souterrain (underground passage) used for storage or refuge.","sources":[{"name":"Megalithic Ireland","url":"https://www.megalithicireland.com/Drumena.htm"},{"name":"Visions of the Past","url":"https://visionsofthepastblog.com/2013/08/09/drumena-cashel-co-down/"},{"name":"Vici.org","url":"https://vici.org/vici/62067/?lang=en"}]},{"name":"Dunnaman Castle","lat":54.252,"lng":-5.898,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"motte","era":"12th century","condition":"intact","description":"A ruined motte-and-bailey on a drumlin hill in County Down, one of many small Norman fortifications that once dotted the Lecale landscape like chess pieces on a green board.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/dunnaman-castle.jpg","rating":3.1,"reviewCount":10,"county":"County Down","tags":["hilltop","free-entry","norman"],"access":"free","_index":1223,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/dunnaman-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/dunnaman-castle-3.jpg"],"history":"A Norman motte-and-bailey castle on a drumlin in the Lecale area of County Down. Part of the extensive network of Anglo-Norman fortifications established after John de Courcy's invasion of Ulster in 1177. The earthwork mound with its surrounding ditch is typical of the rapid fortifications thrown up across the conquered territory. Views extend across the rolling drumlin landscape.","sources":[{"name":"Discover Northern Ireland","url":"https://discovernorthernireland.com/things-to-do"}]},{"name":"Kilclief Castle","lat":54.328,"lng":-5.582,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"tower house","era":"15th century","condition":"intact","description":"A remarkably intact 15th-century tower house on the shore of Strangford Lough, built by a bishop who was defrocked for living in sin—the earliest dateable tower house in County Down.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/08/Kilclief_Castle%2C_Geograph.jpg/500px-Kilclief_Castle%2C_Geograph.jpg","rating":3.6,"reviewCount":42,"county":"County Down","tags":["well-preserved","medieval","coastal","free-entry"],"access":"free","_index":1224,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/kilclief-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/kilclief-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/kilclief-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/kilclief-castle-5.jpg"],"history":"Built between 1413 and 1441, reputedly by John Sely, Bishop of Down. This makes it the earliest datable tower house in County Down and a key benchmark for dating others in the region. Bishop Sely was ejected from his office in 1443 for living at the castle with a married woman, Lettice Thomas. The well-preserved tower has twin front turrets and fine views over Strangford Lough.","sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia – Kilclief Castle","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kilclief_Castle"},{"name":"Discover Northern Ireland","url":"https://discovernorthernireland.com/things-to-do/kilclief-castle-p676221"},{"name":"Dept for Communities NI","url":"https://www.communities-ni.gov.uk/heritage-sites/kilclief-castle"}]},{"name":"Walshestown Castle","lat":54.368,"lng":-5.658,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"tower house","era":"15th-16th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A modest tower house ruin in the gentle countryside of County Down, a forgotten fragment of the medieval Anglo-Norman settlement of Lecale.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/walshestown-castle.jpg","rating":3.1,"reviewCount":10,"county":"County Down","tags":["ruins-romantic","free-entry","medieval"],"access":"free","_index":1225,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/walshestown-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/walshestown-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/walshestown-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/walshestown-castle-5.jpg"],"history":"A small tower house in the Lecale area of County Down, part of the dense network of fortified dwellings built in the 15th-16th centuries across this Anglo-Norman settled region. The Walshes were one of the Old English families established in the area after the Norman conquest. The ruined tower stands in farmland, quietly crumbling.","sources":[{"name":"Discover Northern Ireland","url":"https://discovernorthernireland.com"}]},{"name":"Ballynafoy Castle","lat":54.405,"lng":-5.608,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"tower house","era":"15th-16th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A small, rarely visited tower house ruin near Strangford in County Down, standing in quiet farmland as a reminder of the fortified landscape of medieval Lecale.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/ballynafoy-castle.jpg","rating":3,"reviewCount":8,"county":"County Down","tags":["ruins-romantic","free-entry","medieval","remote"],"access":"free","_index":1226,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/ballynafoy-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/ballynafoy-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/ballynafoy-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/ballynafoy-castle-5.jpg"],"history":"A ruined tower house in the Lecale district of County Down, near Strangford. One of many small fortified residences built in the 15th-16th centuries across this densely settled Anglo-Norman region. The tower's remains show typical features of Ulster tower houses including thick walls and narrow window openings.","sources":[{"name":"Discover Northern Ireland","url":"https://discovernorthernireland.com"}]},{"name":"Castle Caldwell","lat":54.498,"lng":-7.868,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"17th century","condition":"ruin","description":"Atmospheric ruins on a wooded peninsula jutting into Lower Lough Erne, where a famous fiddler's memorial warns musicians to 'keep neatly on your seat'.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/castle-caldwell.jpg","rating":3.3,"reviewCount":20,"county":"County Fermanagh","tags":["ruins-romantic","woodland","riverside","free-entry","atmospheric"],"access":"free","_index":1227,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/castle-caldwell-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/castle-caldwell-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/castle-caldwell-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/castle-caldwell-5.jpg"],"history":"A Plantation-era castle built by the Caldwell family in the early 17th century on a peninsula in Lower Lough Erne, County Fermanagh. The estate was known for its hospitality; a memorial stone at the gate commemorates Denis McCabe, a fiddler who drowned in 1770 when he fell from a boat after too much drink, bearing the warning to musicians. The ruins and surrounding forest are now a nature reserve managed by the RSPB.","sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia – Castle Caldwell","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Castle_Caldwell"},{"name":"RSPB – Castle Caldwell","url":"https://www.rspb.org.uk/reserves-and-events/reserves-a-z/castle-caldwell"}]},{"name":"Portora Castle","lat":54.345,"lng":-7.652,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"17th century","condition":"ruin","description":"An Elizabethan fortress ruin overlooking Lough Erne near Enniskillen, neighbour to the famous school where Oscar Wilde and Samuel Beckett were once pupils.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/portora-castle.jpg","rating":3.2,"reviewCount":14,"county":"County Fermanagh","tags":["ruins-romantic","riverside","free-entry","atmospheric"],"access":"free","_index":1228,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/portora-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/portora-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/portora-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/portora-castle-5.jpg"],"history":"Built c.1612-18 as a Plantation castle for Sir William Cole, one of the original planters of Enniskillen. The castle controlled a strategic point on Lough Erne. It was damaged during the Williamite wars and fell into ruin. Adjacent Portora Royal School, founded in 1608, educated both Oscar Wilde and Samuel Beckett. The castle ruins stand on a wooded hill with fine views over the lough.","sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia – Portora Castle","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portora_Castle"},{"name":"Discover Northern Ireland","url":"https://discovernorthernireland.com/things-to-do/portora-castle"}]},{"name":"Aghinver Castle","lat":54.415,"lng":-7.758,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"17th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A ruined Plantation-era tower on the shores of Lough Erne in Fermanagh, slowly surrendering to ivy and the soft Irish rain.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/aghinver-castle.jpg","rating":3.1,"reviewCount":10,"county":"County Fermanagh","tags":["ruins-romantic","riverside","free-entry","remote"],"access":"free","_index":1229,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/aghinver-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/aghinver-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/aghinver-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/aghinver-castle-5.jpg"],"history":"A Plantation-period castle on the shores of Lough Erne, County Fermanagh. Built in the early 17th century during the Ulster Plantation, when English and Scottish settlers were granted confiscated lands. The tower house served as a fortified dwelling in this lakeland frontier region. Now a crumbling ruin surrounded by farmland on the lough shore.","sources":[{"name":"Discover Northern Ireland","url":"https://discovernorthernireland.com"}]},{"name":"Belle Isle Castle","lat":54.218,"lng":-7.375,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"17th-18th century","condition":"restored","description":"A grand estate on an island in Upper Lough Erne, where centuries of Irish history—from the McManus chroniclers of the Annals of Ulster to the Dukes of Abercorn—unfold amid tranquil lakeland.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/belle-isle-castle.jpg","rating":3.6,"reviewCount":40,"county":"County Fermanagh","tags":["island","gardens","atmospheric","wedding-venue"],"access":"paid","_index":1230,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/belle-isle-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/belle-isle-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/belle-isle-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/belle-isle-castle-5.jpg"],"history":"Set on what was once an island in Upper Lough Erne, County Fermanagh, Belle Isle was home to the McManus clan who compiled the Annals of Ulster. Sir Paul Gore acquired it in the Plantation era, and Sir Ralph Gore built the present house c.1700. The 1st Earl of Ross was born here in 1725. A Tudor-style wing with minstrels' gallery was added in 1907. Now owned by the Duke of Abercorn and available for holiday lets.","sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia – Belle Isle Castle","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belle_Isle_Castle"},{"name":"Belle Isle Estate","url":"https://belle-isle.com/explore-belle-isle-estate/history/"}]},{"name":"Crevenish Castle","lat":54.438,"lng":-7.708,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"17th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A compact Plantation tower house on the shore of Lower Lough Erne, its angular silhouette reflected in the still waters of Fermanagh's island-studded lake.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f6/Crevenish_Castle.jpg/500px-Crevenish_Castle.jpg","rating":3.2,"reviewCount":12,"county":"County Fermanagh","tags":["ruins-romantic","riverside","free-entry"],"access":"free","_index":1231,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/crevenish-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/crevenish-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/crevenish-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/crevenish-castle-5.jpg"],"history":"A Plantation-era castle on the southern shore of Lower Lough Erne, County Fermanagh. Built in the early 17th century as part of the Ulster Plantation, it served as a fortified residence for settlers in this remote lakeland region. The small tower house retains its basic structure with fine views across the lough to its many wooded islands.","sources":[{"name":"Discover Northern Ireland","url":"https://discovernorthernireland.com"}]},{"name":"Augher Castle","lat":54.418,"lng":-7.178,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"17th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A fortified Plantation house in the Clogher Valley of County Tyrone, where Scottish settlers built solidly against the threats of a frontier existence.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/augher-castle.jpg","rating":3.1,"reviewCount":10,"county":"County Tyrone","tags":["medieval","free-entry"],"access":"exterior-only","_index":1232,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/augher-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/augher-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/augher-castle-4.jpg"],"history":"A Plantation castle built c.1615 in the village of Augher, County Tyrone, in the Clogher Valley. Erected by Scottish settlers as part of the Ulster Plantation, it was a substantial fortified house designed for defence in uncertain times. The castle was damaged during the 1641 rebellion and repaired. It later served as a private residence and stands near the village centre.","sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia – Augher","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Augher"}]},{"name":"Favour Royal Castle","lat":54.388,"lng":-7.028,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"17th century","condition":"ruin","description":"The romantic ruin of a Plantation castle in the rolling Tyrone countryside, its name suggesting the royal favour that granted these Ulster lands to English settlers.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/favour-royal-castle.jpg","rating":3.1,"reviewCount":9,"county":"County Tyrone","tags":["ruins-romantic","free-entry","woodland"],"access":"exterior-only","_index":1234,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/favour-royal-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/favour-royal-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/favour-royal-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/favour-royal-castle-5.jpg"],"history":"A Plantation-era castle in the townland of Favour Royal, near Augher, County Tyrone. Built in the early 17th century, the name derives from the royal grant of land. The estate was held by the Mervyn family from the Plantation period. The castle ruins stand in parkland amid the gentle hills of the Clogher Valley. The estate later became known for its gardens.","sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia – Favour Royal","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Favour_Royal"}]},{"name":"Roughan Castle","lat":54.498,"lng":-6.908,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"17th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A striking three-storey Plantation tower house overlooking a small lough near Dungannon, built by the Stewart family who gave their name to nearby Stewartstown.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/scraped-roughan.jpg","rating":3.2,"reviewCount":14,"county":"County Tyrone","tags":["ruins-romantic","riverside","free-entry"],"access":"free","_index":1235,"history":"Built c.1618 by Andrew Stewart junior, who acquired the land of Ballokevan between 1610 and 1619 as part of the Plantation of Ulster. The castle overlooks Roughan Lough near Newmills, County Tyrone. After Andrew's death it passed to his brother John, then to Robert Stewart, whose first wife was reportedly Catherine O'Neill, granddaughter of Hugh, last Earl of Tyrone. Now a scheduled State Care monument.","sources":[{"name":"Castles.nl – Roughan Castle","url":"https://www.castles.nl/roughan-castle"},{"name":"Military Wiki","url":"https://military-history.fandom.com/wiki/Roughan_Castle"}]},{"name":"Brackagh Castle","lat":54.548,"lng":-7.098,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"tower house","era":"17th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A weathered tower house fragment in the mossy fields of County Tyrone, a quiet survivor from the turbulent Plantation era in the heart of O'Neill country.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/brackagh-castle.jpg","rating":3,"reviewCount":7,"county":"County Tyrone","tags":["ruins-romantic","free-entry","remote"],"access":"free","_index":1236,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/brackagh-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/brackagh-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/brackagh-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/brackagh-castle-5.jpg"],"history":"A ruined tower house in the townland of Brackagh, County Tyrone. Dating to the Plantation period of the early 17th century, it was one of many fortified dwellings erected across Ulster as settlers established themselves in formerly Gaelic territory. The fragmentary ruins stand in farmland, overlooked by the hills of mid-Tyrone.","sources":[{"name":"Discover Northern Ireland","url":"https://discovernorthernireland.com"}]},{"name":"Bellaghy Bawn","lat":54.752,"lng":-6.518,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"fortification","era":"17th century","condition":"restored","description":"A restored Plantation-era fortified house in County Derry, now a museum and cultural centre honouring Nobel laureate Seamus Heaney, who grew up in its shadow.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/bellaghy-bawn.jpg","rating":3.7,"reviewCount":55,"county":"County Derry","tags":["well-preserved","museum","free-entry"],"access":"free","_index":1237,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/bellaghy-bawn-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/bellaghy-bawn-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/bellaghy-bawn-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/bellaghy-bawn-5.jpg"],"history":"Construction began c.1614 under John Rowley and was continued by Sir Baptist Jones after Rowley's death in 1617. The bawn (defensive enclosure) and fortified house were part of the London companies' Plantation settlement. Burned during the 1641 rebellion, it was rebuilt and later restored. Now serves as a heritage centre and exhibition space celebrating local poet Seamus Heaney, who was born nearby in 1939.","sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia – Bellaghy Bawn","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bellaghy_Bawn"},{"name":"Discover Northern Ireland","url":"https://discovernorthernireland.com/things-to-do/bellaghy-bawn-p675661"}]},{"name":"Moneymore Castle","lat":54.688,"lng":-6.748,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"17th century","condition":"ruin","description":"The faintest traces of a Plantation-era settlement in one of Ireland's earliest planned towns, laid out by the Drapers' Company of London in the 1620s.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/moneymore-castle.jpg","rating":3.1,"reviewCount":10,"county":"County Derry","tags":["free-entry"],"access":"free","_index":1238,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/moneymore-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/moneymore-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/moneymore-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/moneymore-castle-5.jpg"],"history":"Moneymore in County Londonderry was one of the first planned Plantation towns in Ulster, established by the Worshipful Company of Drapers from London in the 1620s. A fortified house or bawn was built as part of the settlement. Little of the original castle survives, but the wide main street and planned layout of the town reflect its Plantation origins.","sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia – Moneymore","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moneymore"}]},{"name":"Salterstown Castle","lat":54.712,"lng":-6.538,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"fortification","era":"17th century","condition":"ruin","description":"The crumbling walls of a Plantation bawn near the shores of Lough Neagh, built by the Salters' Company of London in their allocated portion of Ulster.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/salterstown-castle.jpg","rating":3,"reviewCount":8,"county":"County Derry","tags":["ruins-romantic","free-entry"],"access":"free","_index":1239,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/salterstown-castle-2.jpg"],"history":"A Plantation-era fortified settlement built by the Worshipful Company of Salters from London on their allocated lands in County Londonderry, near the shore of Lough Neagh. Constructed in the early 17th century as part of the organised colonisation of Ulster. The bawn and castle ruins reflect the systematic nature of the Plantation, where each London livery company was assigned territory to develop.","sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia – Salterstown","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salterstown"}]},{"name":"Ballycastle Bawn","lat":55.202,"lng":-6.238,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"fortification","era":"17th century","condition":"ruin","description":"Fragmentary remains of a Plantation bawn in the windswept north Antrim coast town, where the Ould Lammas Fair has drawn crowds every August since 1606.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/ballycastle-bawn.jpg","rating":3,"reviewCount":7,"county":"County Antrim","tags":["free-entry","coastal"],"access":"free","_index":1240,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/ballycastle-bawn-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/ballycastle-bawn-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/ballycastle-bawn-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/ballycastle-bawn-5.jpg"],"history":"A Plantation-era bawn (fortified enclosure) in Ballycastle, County Antrim. Built in the early 17th century as part of the settlement of the north Antrim coast. Ballycastle grew around this and other fortifications established by Scottish settlers. The town is famous for its annual Ould Lammas Fair, held since 1606, one of the oldest traditional fairs in Ireland.","sources":[{"name":"Discover Northern Ireland","url":"https://discovernorthernireland.com/things-to-do/ballycastle"}]},{"name":"Tandragee Castle","lat":54.358,"lng":-6.478,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"17th century / 19th century","condition":"intact","description":"A grand castellated mansion crowning a wooded hill above the town of Tandragee—once an O'Hanlon stronghold, now home to the famous Tayto crisp factory.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/tandragee-castle.jpg","rating":3.4,"reviewCount":25,"county":"County Armagh","tags":["hilltop","victorian"],"access":"exterior-only","_index":1242,"gallery":["https://pub-865f4a8498e64980801e4e498b53f5c0.r2.dev/wiki-tandragee-castle.jpg"],"history":"The site was originally an O'Hanlon fort, later rebuilt as a Plantation castle by the Hamilton family in the early 17th century. The current castellated mansion dates largely from 1837, designed by William Murray. It was used as a military hospital during WWII. Since 1956, it has been the headquarters of Tayto (Northern Ireland), makers of the beloved cheese and onion crisps. The castle is not open to the public but dominates the Tandragee skyline.","sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia – Tandragee Castle","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tandragee_Castle"}]},{"name":"Charlemont Fort","lat":54.458,"lng":-6.728,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"fortification","era":"17th century","condition":"ruin","description":"The earthwork remains of a strategic Tudor and later star fort on the River Blackwater, once the key to controlling the passage into the heart of O'Neill territory.","image":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b2/Charlemont%2C_co._Armagh_-_The_State_of_the_Fortes_of_Ireland_in_1624_%281624%29%2C_ff.38v-39_-_BL_Add_MS_24200.jpg/500px-Charlemont%2C_co._Armagh_-_The_State_of_the_Fortes_of_Ireland_in_1624_%281624%29%2C_ff.38v-39_-_BL_Add_MS_24200.jpg","rating":3.3,"reviewCount":18,"county":"County Armagh","tags":["free-entry","riverside","atmospheric"],"access":"free","_index":1243,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/charlemont-fort-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/charlemont-fort-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/charlemont-fort-4.jpg"],"history":"Founded in 1602 by Lord Mountjoy during the Nine Years' War as an English outpost to control the Blackwater crossing into Tyrone. Named after Lord Charlemont, it was substantially rebuilt as a star-shaped fort in the 17th century. It was besieged during the 1641 rebellion and the Williamite wars. Owen Roe O'Neill captured it in 1646. Now largely earthworks beside the village of Charlemont, County Armagh.","sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia – Charlemont Fort","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charlemont_Fort"}]},{"name":"Tynan Castle","lat":54.328,"lng":-6.808,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"castle","era":"19th century","condition":"ruin","description":"A Victorian Gothic Revival castle in County Armagh, privately held by the Stronge family for centuries—tragically attacked during the Troubles in 1981.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/tynan-castle.jpg","rating":3.2,"reviewCount":14,"county":"County Armagh","tags":["gothic","victorian"],"access":"exterior-only","_index":1244,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/tynan-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/tynan-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/tynan-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/tynan-castle-5.jpg"],"history":"A Gothic Revival castle near Tynan village, County Armagh, seat of the Stronge family since the Plantation era. The current building dates mainly from the 19th century with ornate Gothic detailing. In January 1981, Sir Norman Stronge, Speaker of the NI Senate, and his son James were killed in an IRA attack and the castle was set ablaze. The ruins remain in private ownership surrounded by parkland.","sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia – Tynan Abbey","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tynan_Abbey"}]},{"name":"Coney Island Castle","lat":54.428,"lng":-6.678,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"tower house","era":"Medieval","condition":"ruin","description":"The scant remains of a tower on a tiny island in Lough Neagh—reputedly the inspiration for New York's famous Coney Island, via Irish emigrant memory.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/coney-island-castle.jpg","rating":3.3,"reviewCount":18,"county":"County Armagh","tags":["island","ruins-romantic","free-entry","remote"],"access":"free","_index":1245,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/coney-island-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/coney-island-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/coney-island-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/coney-island-castle-5.jpg"],"history":"A small island in Lough Neagh off the southern shore near Maghery, County Armagh. The remains of an O'Neill tower house stand on the island, dating to the medieval period. Local tradition claims that Irish emigrants named New York's Coney Island after this place, though the connection is debated. The island is accessible by boat and is now a nature area rich in birdlife.","sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia – Coney Island, Lough Neagh","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coney_Island,_Lough_Neagh"}]},{"name":"Donnaghdee Castle","lat":54.642,"lng":-5.532,"country":"Northern Ireland","type":"motte","era":"12th century","condition":"intact","description":"The fragmentary remains of a Norman motte at Donaghadee on the County Down coast, where the shortest sea crossing to Scotland has been used for millennia.","image":"https://img.castlecore.uk/donnaghdee-castle.jpg","rating":3.1,"reviewCount":10,"county":"County Down","tags":["coastal","free-entry","norman"],"access":"free","_index":1338,"gallery":["https://img.castlecore.uk/donnaghdee-castle-2.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/donnaghdee-castle-3.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/donnaghdee-castle-4.jpg","https://img.castlecore.uk/donnaghdee-castle-5.jpg"],"history":"Donaghadee on the County Down coast lies at the closest point between Ireland and Scotland (just 21 miles to Portpatrick). A Norman motte was raised here in the 12th century to control this strategic crossing point. The earthwork mound near the harbour is all that remains. The town later became an important packet port for mail and passengers to Scotland.","sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia – Donaghadee","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donaghadee"}]}];